{
  "text": "The three-dimensional structure of the SMN protein reveals its key role in the formation of a robust multimeric complex that assembles a diverse cohort of RNP complexes, including snRNPs. Interactions involving the C-terminus of SMN and the B-D3 dimer play a critical role in the completion of the Sm ring. Comparison of the SMN and SMN\u03947 structures supports the loss of snRNP assembly as being the key contributor to the atrophy of neurons. While other functions that have not yet been identified may contribute, the structural differences show that SMN\u03947 has limited stability, loss of ability to assemble the Sm ring and cannot mediate adequate levels of snRNP assembly. This outcome has implications for amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, ALS, which like SMA is characterized by the progressive degeneration of motor neurons [CITATION_1] . Genetic screening of ALS patients has revealed altered genes encoding proteins associated with the SMN complex and RNA metabolism, and spliceosome integrity is lost in both diseases [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . These common features between SMA and ALS, in the context of the SMN model, suggest that some forms of ALS may arise due to genetic loss of RNP function.",
  "citation_candidates": [
